How football's financial rules will affect Neymar's move to Paris
Rules restricting the funding of European football clubs will in no way undermine Neymar's record-breaking transfer from Barcelona, Spain, to Paris-Saint Germain, France.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by the EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the authority to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
Financial Fair Play (FFP) rules , which were introduced by UEFA in 2011 stipend that PSG will have to demonstrate that Neymar's transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid a sum of EUR 222 million alone to buy Neymar out of his contract and Neymar will claim a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
There are several financial conditions following for Neymar's transfer to France.
With the PSG team being funded by a wealthy Qatari family that made its fortune in selling energy, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already star football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums to buy players, but on the other hand have to prove legal sources of income, allowing them to cover the overheads of the football-related business.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini, after being appointed to the post of director of UEFA in 2007.
The former French player believed that the clubs that took debt in pursuit of new reinforcements would ultimately cheat and risk bankruptcy if the banks or the owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, the FFP redirected its attention from club debts to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich with Chelsea in 2003 - buying a club with potential and spending exortious sums on players y to build a global brand - was suddenly not so advantageous.
Under the current three-year trial period, which will end in 2018, clubs may report a loss of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite Platini's due exit from his post in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Čeferin, is committed to advocating a ban on excessive spending.
"FFP rules are still in place and we are determined to strengthen them in the future," Andrea Traverso, who oversees compliance with FFP rules, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG has paid the amount for the redemption of Neymar in a one-off payment, it can spread the amount for the purposes of the accounts over the entire duration of the contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down to €44.4 million each year for five years.
The first wave of the FFP's highest sanctions was hit by PSG in 2014, along with Manchester City, which is owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG took a fine of EUR 60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to EUR 20 million - and a order to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is wary of teams that can try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their income through companies associated with club owners.
Thus, even if the Qatari company sponsors PSG, once the funding exceeds the value of the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the statement of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after deciding that the funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
Some of the Neymar's income in PSG could be paid for by the 2022 FIFA World Cup Organising Commission in Qatar, according to some reports.
However, PSG and the leaders of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar have denied the fat that Neymat should become a fame-fighting ambassador and that such a maneuver would be easily exposed by UEFY officials.
Previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
According to the insider-initiated UEFA on Tuesday, no investigation has been initiated in the matter of Neymar's transfer to PSG.
The source of the report wished to remain anonymous as it is not entitled to comment on the situation with PSG, The Associated Press reported.
The latest published accounts show that PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of EUR 10 million and a turnover of EUR 542.4 million.
The accounts for the current financial year have not yet been made public.
