NHS prescribes controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
Patients will gain access from September to 'transformative' treatment to HIV prevention based on a Supreme Court's decision to fund the NHS drug.
The English National Health Service (NSH) reported that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered via the health service to approximately 10,000 patients in the three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to finance the probationary period after the appeals court supported the Supreme Court's decision last year to say that the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP despite the statement that the medicine should be funded by the local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was taken by the NHS of England from the mouths of Director-General Simon Stevens as a 'significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
The Sexual Health Clinic in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 there will be a full implementation across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission between patients at risk.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there are a sufficient number of specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent the infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include homosexual or bisexual men, transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who are successfully untreated.
The clinics will identify eligible participants who sign up to agree to participate in the testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with the GP in the UK can also sign up at their local sexual health clinic to apply for potential participation in the testing.
The program will cost the taxpayer £10 million and the NHS of England signed a contract this week to distribute medicines following the international public contract.
The test period is proposed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: 'This important intervention should be replenished and fully energized and fully widespread and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It's another milestone in a more than 30-year quest to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, Executive Director of NAT (National Aids Trust) said: 'We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and at risk for patients, it will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
From September, the NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to cajole a partner, leading to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.'
Ian Green, managing director of Terrence Higgins Trust said: 'The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure that it is available to each patient.
We now have a test drug at our disposal, PrEP, and we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of being infected with HIV.'
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: 'The start of the PrEP test period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and endanglement of this life-threatening infection.
The ensuing tests will take us one step closer to a full understanding of PrEP's benefits.
It is now important that we launch the tests as soon as possible throughout the country to protect those who are exposed to HIV, bringing to an end to the spread of HIV in society together.'
