Red meat, dairy and chocolate may relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The non-healthy disease, which affects up to 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to use meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, University researchers found that the essential tryptophan's essential amino acid in the protein helps to create immune cells that promote bowel resistance.
Head of study dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the degradation of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tilts to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting the body's tolerance in the stomach of mice with a particular bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan to form cells - one of the building blocks of the proteins.
To this, Professor Colonna said, "We have found a link between a type of bacterium - the Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a normal part of the intestinal microbiome and the development of cells that promote the tolerance of the body.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more these immune cells had."
At the same time, he suggested that if the same thing turned out to be true for humans, then a combination of L. reuterium and tryptophan-rich bacteria would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory bowel environment.
Postgraduate researcher dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in the study of a certain type of body tolerance of immune cells, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mouse-behaving separately disguise the cells were missing.
It was derived from the fact that one group of mice has a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally dwells in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mice was tested by the DNA-mounted method and researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that were missing from the second group of mice.
Mwes, which were bred in a sterile environment and lacked the gut microbiome - so they did not develop this type of immune cells - was administered by L. reuteri - and created immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affects the immune system, researchers grew L reuterium in the liquid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were stored in isolation.
The immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After the active ingredient was removed from the liquid, it was revealed to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-octic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mouse diet, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. At the same time, after the splits of tryptophan, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known if the tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri bacteria cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but transcripts in the tryptophan-related genes were found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: "Each of us should probably seek to develop these cells because they control the inflammatory intrusion of the intestines' inner surface.
Potentially high level of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase the cell population."
