Get to know the plant with one click.
Students with herbarian creation and ordinary plant lovers will be helped by the new free application Pl@ntNet.
When they're interested in what plant they've just come across on a walk, this app will advise them.
All they'll have to do is photograph the plant, and the app recognizes what kind it is.
The new app, which is available for both iOS and Android, was presented on Tuesday by representatives of the CEE's Centre for Ethical and Environmental Education in the Roostern of Bratislava as part of the Secret Life of the City project.
The project was also involved in pupils from 50 Czech and Slovak schools, who photographed and added plants from their surroundings with the app's apps with the teachers.
The newly created French app is free to download on the Secret Life of the City website.
The main goal of the French programmers was for as many people as possible to contribute to the app with their images, thereby increasing the number of plants that the application can recognize.
"Already children who can hold a tablet or mobile phone in their hand can go to the forest," said this project's coordinator, Ivana Poláčková.
Based on a high-quality photo of the flower, leaf or fruit of the plant, the application can recognize its name in seconds, which is then assigned under the photo in both Czech and Slovak.
The French allowed us to translate the app into the Secret Life of the City project into Slovak and Czech.
It is therefore welcome for users to contribute to the app after opening an account with a picture of a plant that is not yet found in the database.
"The French will evaluate whether it is beneficial and then add it to the database," Poláčková informed.
GMB concerns about investment in McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The union is demanding assurances from the managers of the biscuit maker McVitie's about the long-term production commitment at the Glasgow factory.
The Scottish GMB trade union said the company was silent for the time being about any investment in the Tollcross plant.
The factory employs more than 500 employees who produce, among other products, the Hobnob and Rich Tea biscuits.
The owner of McVitie's, Pladis, said it had invested more than £5 million in the area in the previous few years.
It added that the employees and trade union representatives would be "between the first informed" in the event of changes to the operation of the factory.
In a letter to the builder, the GMB, Scottish unions expressed their concern that McVitie's would "not get its promises to fund and upgrade production lines."
GMB's main organizer Drew Duffy added: "The fact that we have not received a clear response from the site supervisor about the needs of the company and the future investment plan in Tollcross is very worrying for our members.
Generations of many families worked here, and employees come mostly from the local community and the Glasgow area, where working at the local factory is a critical pillar of decent employment in the area of high unemployment and social separations.
From a point of view of work, salaries, and utility - and despite the outlook for Brexit, rising cost of living, and falling slow production - the eastern part of Glasgow needs a desperately prosperous producer like McVitie's."
A spokesperson for Pladis said: "The Tollcross manager received a letter from GMB only yesterday and the company will issue a statement as soon as possible, as we appreciate the continuing commitment to the employees and representatives of the unions.
A regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives in Tollcross took place two months ago and many problems were openly discussed at this meeting.
We were talking to employees that, as in all companies operating in extremely competitive and insecure economic conditions, we assess our operations on a regular basis, which is true for all our operations, so that we can continue to successfully compete with others.
To this she added: "In recent years, we have invested £5 million in the Tollcross area, particularly in production lines and streamlining operations.
We greatly appreciate the heritage of Tollcross and the localities and, in the event of any changes in the operation of the factory, the employees and representatives of the unions will be informed without delay."
Did PSG warn Barcelona to move Neymar three years ago?
La Liga may regret his interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain will not allow Neymar to his side in his bid for her side after she put down £189m, the amount needed to buy Neymar out of the contract, but did this French team warn Barcelona of their record-breaking raid three years ago?
This sensational transfer has stirred up the waters of the summer transfers. The Ligue 1 Club is prepared to surpass more than twice the previous record amount for Paul Pogba's transfer to Manchester United, which paid £800m for him last year.
After confirming and completing the transfer, Neymar will become the world's most expensive player and, at the same time, the highest-paid professional athlete in the world - after tax, he will receive over £500,000 a week from the PSG team.
Barcelona is outraged in the way Neymar has emerged from his contract, despite the fact that a confidential source has confirmed that the club has always tried to accommodate Neymar in everything since his arrival from Santos in 2013.
But was the football world alerted to this fact to the PSG president three years ago?
When Manchester City expressed their interest in Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi warned all the club interested in taking over one of PSG's best players.
"I'm not worried because as soon as someone tries to get one of our players, then we will certainly reach out to one of their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
"We respect all the clubs.
But if they're trying to get one of our players, they'll face the consequences."
Barcelona seems to have crossed the imaginary line when they expressed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti in the summer.
PSG made it clear that under no circumstances would they authorise the Italian representative to leave. It is therefore possible that Barcelona is now swallowing a bitter pill for their bold behaviour with the departure of Neymar.
Who will explain the sanctions?
Does political punishment have broadly understood rules?
