It, too, is the idea of sanctions like straw from shoes.
Those things can't be lumped together.
Maduro's Venezuela really set off on the road to dictatorship, even totalitarianism.
China is not just behaving as the US president would like.
Russia is a chapter in itself.
But if someone wanted to summarise all of this in such a way that even a common voter, an American, European or another, understood what the system of rules was about, the policy of sanctions was based on, it would be an almost impossible task.
In sanctions against Russia, President Trump merely lands with what President Obama has already set up, only giving it an implementing stamp.
So why such a stir?
Last year, Europe was terrified that if Trump won the US election, he would hug Putin and call off the sanctions.
Terrible image.
But in practice, it is the other way around.
With Trump, sanctions are not loosening, but they are tightening.
But Europe is even more terrified.
German Minister Zypries says the Trump sanctions violate international law.
That's just the sanctions approved by the UN Security Council?
